data.content:
MSTest has `CollectionAssert` and more specific asserts that give better failure messages than `Assert.IsTrue`:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Assert count explicitly — failure shows "Expected:3, Actual:X"
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Assert all elements satisfy a condition
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");

    // Assert a specific element exists
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"), "Expected an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

- **`Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count)`** — on failure you see the actual count, unlike `Assert.IsTrue` which just says "expected True, got False"
- **Add message strings** to `Assert.IsTrue` when using predicates, so failures are diagnosable
- **`CollectionAssert`** is useful for deeper checks:

```csharp
// Verify exact contents (order-insensitive)
CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expectedList, actualList);

// Verify exact contents + order
CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expectedList, actualList);

// Verify all items are of a type
CollectionAssert.AllAreSatisfy(users, u => Assert.IsTrue(((User)u).IsActive));

// Contains / DoesNotContain
CollectionAssert.Contains(users, specificUser);
```

**Rule of thumb:** prefer the most specific assert available — it produces the most helpful failure message.
